    "recap_headline": "Abilene Christian",
    "recap_text": "ABILENE, Texas \u2014\nThe Abilene Christian baseball team pounded out 17 hits for a season-high 22 runs during a 22-11 run-ruled victory over Loyola Marymount on Sunday at Bullock Brothers Ballpark at Crutcher Scott Field.\nThe win puts the Wildcats back at .500 for the season at 10-10 overall, while LMU dropped to 7-15.\nThe temperature was around 80 degrees at first pitch, but steadily dropped as a strong cold front made its way into Abilene. A constant wind of 25-30 miles per hour, with gusts to 40 mph, pushed out to right field which helped the teams combine for 11 home runs in just 6.5 innings of play. In addition to the Wildcats' five homers, they also smacked a season-high six doubles and induced 11 walks.\nGrant Watkins\nfinished with 7 RBI, a new career-best, on a pair of 3-run round-trippers and a sacrifice fly.\nDiego Cardenas\nwent 3/5 with two doubles and a long ball, and\nNick Arias\ndrove in a career-high 5 runs with two 2-RBI doubles to deep center field.\nZandt Payne\nsmashed two home runs, including a solo home run to start the scoring in the first.\nACU added seven runs in the second.\u00a0Abilene Wylie H.S. graduate\nJT Thompson\ndoubled to right center, and\nBrady Gray's\nsingle advanced him to third. A two-RBI double by Arias, and a three-run homer from Watkins\u00a0contributed to a seven-run inning.\nIn the third inning, Watkins again homered, this time a three-run shot to center field, increasing the lead to 11\u20134.\nThe Cats continued to pummel\u00a0Lion pitchers in the fourth with 11 runs.\nGavin Brzozowski\nwalked with the bases loaded, followed by Arias being hit by a pitch to score another run. Payne homered to deep right, his second home run of the game, to bring plate three more runs. Cardenas hit an RBI double to deep center, and came around to score on a single by Brady Ladasau who wound up coming home on a wild pitch. Arias crushed his second 2-RBI double to bring in Thompson and\nBrady Gray\nto put ACU in front 22-6. Gray had a career-high three runs.\nLoyola Marymount added three runs in the fifth and two in the sixth, but the Wildcats' lead was never in jeopardy.\nDavid Jeon\nearned the win by delivering a perfect relief appearance, pitching the top of the seventh without allowing a hit or a walk, while striking out one batter.\nCade McGarrh\n, who started the game, surrendered 4 runs on 4 hits in his 2 1/3 innings of work.\nLogan Young\nprovided much-needed stability by retiring the only two batters he faced in his brief outing, inducing a 6-4-3 double play in the fourth.\nIt is the second time in 11 days the Wildcats have reached the 20-run mark after taking down Stephen F. Austin 20-10 on March 4. The 22 runs are the most ACU has scored in a game since plating 23 against Prairie View A&M on March 9, 2025.\nACU TOP PERFORMERS\nDiego Cardenas\n2 doubles\n1 home run\n3 RBIs\nNick Arias\n3 runs (season high)\n5 RBIs (career high)\n2 doubles\nGrant Watkins\n2 home runs\n7 RBIs (career high)\n2 runs\nZandt Payne\n2 home runs\n4 RBIs\n2 runs\nBrady Gray\n3 runs (career high)\n3 walks\n2 hits\nUP NEXT\nThe Wildcats close out their four-game homestand by taking on the UIW Cardinals on Wednesday, March 18 at Bullock Brothers Ballpark at Crutcher Scott Field. First pitch has been moved up to 4 p.m. to better accommodate travel plans for both teams. Due to the time change, the game will now be broadcast on WAC International instead of ESPN+."
  },
